Montenegro has clearly been on the path to membership in EU with the founding of the Stabilisation and Association Process, which joined Montenegro into an exclusive group with Serbia and other South-East European countries. So far, the shocking news came out of it was announced on 02 June 2015 when Montenegro's integrity was thoroughly questioned by representatives of the EU. In other words, it received a rather unpleasant surprise from its old “BFF” – the EU.
The interest of Montenegrin president, Milo Đukanović, to enhance his public influence by introducing “the concept of resistance” is one of the most pragmatic political acts in its recent history. Đukanović acknowledged the unwillingness of non-violent political opposition to compromise on ethical, moral and political ideas that lead Montenegro into deep crisis. There is no sufficient public capacity to stop or slow the process of destruction.
The roots of alleged resistance are essentially political. The party in government has supported the creation of a unified political elite based on the principle of state-socialism and “mobilised masses” – a model that will result in social deterioration and a ripe opportunity for a coup d'état.
